<paragraph id="8BE836D40701FFD2FD43FA29FF2BAB22" blockId="7.[677,1210,1515,1700]" lastBlockId="8.[113,647,216,1478]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="101" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570701FFDDFCDCFA29FC28AC17" baseAuthorityName="Leske" baseAuthorityYear="1778" box="[826,939,1515,1540]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="7" pageNumber="100" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="setosum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60701FFDDFCDCFA29FC28AC17" box="[826,939,1515,1540]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">D. setosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected from 
<collectingRegion id="4993F8360701FFDDFB6AFA29FD5DAC37" country="Mauritius" name="Port Louis" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">Port Louis</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry id="F34076440701FFDDFD0CF9C8FCD6AC36" box="[746,853,1546,1573]" name="Mauritius" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
), 
<collectingRegion id="4993F8360701FFDDFC83F9C8FC3FAC37" box="[869,956,1546,1572]" country="Indonesia" name="Sulawesi Utara" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">Sulawesi</collectingRegion>
Is. (
<collectingCountry id="F34076440701FFDDFC03F9C8FBCCAC36" box="[997,1103,1546,1573]" name="Indonesia" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
), Nouméa (
<collectingCountry id="F34076440701FFDDFD4AF9E8FCD9AC56" box="[684,858,1578,1605]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
), Luzon (
<collectingCountry id="F34076440701FFDDFC24F9E8FBC2AC56" box="[962,1089,1578,1605]" name="Philippines" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">Philippines</collectingCountry>
), Lizard Is. (
<collectingCountry id="F34076440701FFDDFD4AF988FC8CAC76" box="[684,783,1610,1637]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">Australia</collectingCountry>
) and Suva (
<collectingCountry id="F34076440701FFDDFC76F988FC39AC76" box="[912,954,1610,1637]" name="Fiji" pageId="7" pageNumber="100">Fiji</collectingCountry>
). Adult specimens were found to have mean test diameters of 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310701FFDDFBCCF9A8FBFAAC97" box="[1066,1145,1642,1668]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="100" unit="mm" value="70.0">70 mm</quantity>
(h.d.) (SD ± 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310701FFDDFD0BF94BFCC6ACB7" box="[749,837,1673,1700]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" pageId="7" pageNumber="100" unit="mm" value="3.7">3.7 mm</quantity>
) by 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310701FFDDFC93F94BFC47ACB7" box="[885,964,1673,1700]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="100" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
(v.d.) (SD ± 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310701FFDDFBB5F94BFB2EACB7" box="[1107,1197,1673,1700]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="100" unit="mm" value="2.9">2.9 mm</quantity>
). Maximum test diameters of 
<quantity id="4CAF9B31070EFFD2FE68FF1AFE5AAAE1" box="[398,473,216,242]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.4" pageId="8" pageNumber="101" unit="mm" value="84.0">84 mm</quantity>
(h.d.) by 
<quantity id="4CAF9B31070EFFD2FDDCFF1AFD05AAE1" box="[570,646,216,242]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="101" unit="mm" value="48.0">48 mm</quantity>
(v.d.) were recorded from 
<specimenCount id="9D51FD5D070EFFD2FE71FF3AFDB9AB02" box="[407,570,247,274]" pageId="8" pageNumber="101" type="generic">200 specimens</specimenCount>
examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34D655F070EFFD2FF6EFEF5FE97AFD5" pageId="8" pageNumber="101" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE836D4070EFFD2FF6EFEF5FE02A81C" blockId="8.[113,647,216,1478]" pageId="8" pageNumber="101">
Tests were black with a green tinge occasionally seen on large adult specimens. This was particularly apparent on specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="F3407644070EFFD2FE47FEB4FE4BAB83" box="[417,456,374,400]" name="Fiji" pageId="8" pageNumber="101">Fiji</collectingCountry>
. The typical shape of the test was horizontally circular, with the apical system conspicuously depressed. The ambulacra typically measured 24-30% of the interambulacra measured at the ambitus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D4070EFFD2FF6EFDD7FF7EAE3A" blockId="8.[113,647,216,1478]" pageId="8" pageNumber="101">
The naked median areas had white spots seen both day and night. These white spots were also visible on the naked test (
<figureCitation id="136C2A51070EFFD2FEA2FD96FE14A87D" box="[324,407,596,622]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[113,124,861,878]" captionTargetBox="[188,1134,215,816]" captionTargetId="figure-46@6.[472,756,473,559]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 2. — A-I, photographs of the median areas of the interambulacra, showing the variation in characters that occur: A, Diadema antillarum; B, D. mexicanum; C, D, D. savignyi; E, D. setosum; F, Echinothrix calamaris (brown colour morph); G, E. calamaris (white colour morph); H, E. diadema; I, D. palmeri; J, D. palmeri (whole specimen). Scale bars: A-I, 5 mm; J, 50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401712/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="101">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
) in conjunction with white lines continuing from the spot marking along the mid-lines of the interambulacra to the genital plates. A bold pattern of blue iridophores occurred in this species. These have been described as “spots” by many authors (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B25070EFFD2FEDFFD30FDBCA91E" author="SARASIN P. B. &amp; SARASIN C. F." box="[313,575,754,781]" pageId="8" pageNumber="101" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref10000" refString="SARASIN P. B. &amp; SARASIN C. F. 1887. - Die Augen and das Integument der Diadematiden, in Ergebnisse naturwissenschaftlicher Forschungen auf Ceylon. C. W. Kreidel, Wiesbaden 1: 1 - 18." type="journal article" year="1887">Sarasin &amp; Sarasin 1887</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B25070EFFD2FDADFD31FEACA93F" author="AGASSIZ A. &amp; CLARK H. L." pageId="8" pageNumber="101" pagination="43 - 132" refId="ref8922" refString="AGASSIZ A. &amp; CLARK H. L. 1908. - Hawaiian and other Pacific Echini. The Saleniidae, Arbaciiadae, Aspidodiadematoidae and Diadematidae. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard 34: 43 - 132." type="journal article" year="1908">Agassiz &amp; Clark 1908</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B25070EFFD2FEDCFCD0FE34A93F" author="CLARK H. L." box="[314,439,786,812]" pageId="8" pageNumber="101" pagination="145 - 147" refId="ref9252" refString="CLARK H. L. 1921. - The echinoderm fauna of Torres strait: its composition and its origin. Carnegie Institution of Washington Publication 214: 145 - 147." type="journal article" year="1921">Clark 1921</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B25070EFFD2FE24FCD1FDF9A93F" author="MORTENSEN T." box="[450,634,786,813]" pageId="8" pageNumber="101" refId="ref9794" refString="MORTENSEN T. 1940. - Monograph of the Echinoidea. III (1). C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 370 p." type="book" year="1940">Mortensen 1940</bibRefCitation>
). The pattern of iridophores occurred as a series of “spots” down the mid-lines of the interambulacra. These bisected the naked median areas continuing down just below the ambitus. Lines of blue “spots” also occurred as two series down the ambulacra in some specimens. A single blue “spot” was also present on each genital plate, including above the madreporite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D4070EFFD2FF6EFBEDFEA9AF95" blockId="8.[113,647,216,1478]" pageId="8" pageNumber="101">
The apical system (
<figureCitation id="136C2A51070EFFD2FEB5FBEDFE24AE5A" box="[339,423,1071,1097]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[113,124,680,697]" captionTargetBox="[171,1160,218,635]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[134,1189,203,645]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — Drawings of the apical systems, showing species specific characters of the periproct and genital plates: A, Diadema antillarum; B, D. ascensionis; C, D. mexicanum; D, D. palmeri; E, D. paucispinum; F, D. savignyi; G, D. setosum; H, Echinothrix calamaris (brown colour morph); I, E. calamaris (white colour morph); J, E. diadema. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401708/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="101">Fig. 1G</figureCitation>
) was hemicyclic and measured 22-28% of the test’s horizontal diameter. The periproct measured 12-20% (h.d.) and had a small black anal cone with a distinct orange anal ring, unique to the species. No platelets were present in the membrane. The genital plates had from three to five tubercles present along their inner edge, with green/blue spot markings when viewed on the denuded test (
<figureCitation id="136C2A51070EFFD2FEBCFAEFFE33AF54" box="[346,432,1325,1351]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[113,124,680,697]" captionTargetBox="[171,1160,218,635]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[134,1189,203,645]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — Drawings of the apical systems, showing species specific characters of the periproct and genital plates: A, Diadema antillarum; B, D. ascensionis; C, D. mexicanum; D, D. palmeri; E, D. paucispinum; F, D. savignyi; G, D. setosum; H, Echinothrix calamaris (brown colour morph); I, E. calamaris (white colour morph); J, E. diadema. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401708/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="101">Fig. 1G</figureCitation>
). These represented the location of the blue iridophores observed in living specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D4070EFFD2FF6EFA4EFE97AFD5" blockId="8.[113,647,216,1478]" pageId="8" pageNumber="101">The peristome was grey in colour and measured 40-50% (h.d.).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
